    <h2 id="why-magnesium-sleep">Why Magnesium Is the Most Underrated Sleep Supplement in America</h2>

    <p>While melatonin commands 80% of the sleep supplement market, the mineral that sleep researchers are most excited about is magnesium. The reason is simple: approximately 50% of the American population is magnesium-deficient according to data from the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey, and this deficiency directly impairs your body's ability to initiate and maintain sleep. Magnesium is not a sedative — it is a foundational mineral that your nervous system requires to transition from wakefulness to sleep naturally.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">50%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">of Americans consume less than the recommended daily allowance of magnesium. This subclinical deficiency is linked to <strong>increased cortisol, heightened neural excitability, and impaired GABA receptor function</strong> — all of which directly interfere with sleep onset and maintenance.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Magnesium participates in over 300 enzymatic reactions in the human body, but its role in sleep is mediated through three primary mechanisms. First, it activates GABA receptors — the same targets that prescription sleep medications like Ambien and benzodiazepines act upon — but through a gentle, non-addictive pathway. Second, it suppresses cortisol, the stress hormone that keeps your nervous system in a hypervigilant state incompatible with sleep. Third, it promotes muscle relaxation by regulating calcium flux in muscle cells, reducing the physical tension that many people carry to bed.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
