        <p>The gold standard for sleep. Chelated with glycine — an amino acid with independent sleep-promoting properties. Best absorbed (25-30%), zero GI side effects. Recommended by integrative medicine practitioners.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Magnesium Citrate</strong>
        <p>Second-best for sleep. Good absorption (20-25%) and effective at clinical doses. The trade-off: osmotic laxative effect that can cause loose stools, gas, and cramping in sensitive individuals.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Magnesium L-Threonate</strong>
        <p>Preferentially crosses the blood-brain barrier, making it the most direct form for neurological effects. Limited gummy availability due to large molecular size. Used primarily in cognitive health applications.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Magnesium Oxide</strong>
        <p>The cheapest and worst form for sleep. Only 4% absorption rate, meaning a 400mg dose delivers roughly 16mg of usable magnesium. Primarily useful as a laxative, not a sleep supplement.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2012 double-blind RCT in the <em>Journal of Research in Medical Sciences</em> found that magnesium supplementation in elderly adults with insomnia <strong>significantly improved sleep time, sleep efficiency, and melatonin concentration</strong> while <strong>reducing cortisol levels and insomnia severity scores</strong>. The study also found that magnesium <strong>increased natural melatonin production</strong> — suggesting it may address the root cause that drives people to supplement with exogenous melatonin in the first place.</p>
      <cite>J Research in Medical Sciences, 2012 — Double-blind RCT</cite>
    </div>

    <h3>The Bedtime Routine Connection</h3>

    <p>Magnesium gummies work best when integrated into a consistent bedtime routine. The act of taking a supplement 30-60 minutes before sleep creates a behavioral cue that signals your brain to begin the winding-down process. Combined with other evidence-based practices — dimming lights, reducing screen exposure, and keeping the bedroom at 65-68 degrees Fahrenheit — magnesium becomes the pharmacological anchor of a comprehensive sleep optimization protocol.</p>

