    <!-- INGREDIENT BOX -->
    <div class="ing-box">
      <h4>Magnesium Forms Compared: The Complete Guide</h4>
      <p>Not all magnesium is created equal. The form determines absorption, GI tolerance, and which body systems benefit most. Here is what the science says about each major form.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Magnesium Glycinate</strong>
          <p>Best for sleep. 25-30% absorption, zero GI effects. Glycine chelation provides independent sleep-promoting benefits. Gold standard form recommended by integrative practitioners.<br /><em>Neuropsychopharmacology, 2015</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Magnesium Citrate</strong>
          <p>Second-best for sleep. 20-25% absorption. Effective and affordable, but osmotic laxative effect causes GI issues in 15-20% of users at sleep-relevant doses (250mg+).<br /><em>J Am College of Nutrition, 2007</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Magnesium L-Threonate</strong>
          <p>Preferentially crosses the blood-brain barrier. Best for cognitive function and potentially sleep, but rarely available in gummy format and significantly more expensive.<br /><em>Neuron, 2010 — MIT study</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Magnesium Oxide</strong>
          <p>Worst for sleep. Only 4% absorption. A 400mg dose delivers roughly 16mg of usable magnesium. Primarily useful as an osmotic laxative, not a sleep supplement.<br /><em>J Am College of Nutrition, 2003</em></p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="info-cards">
        <div class="info-card">
          <strong>Optimal bedtime dose</strong>
          <p>200-400mg of elemental magnesium taken 30-60 minutes before bed. Start at 200mg and increase gradually. Doses above 400mg from supplements alone may cause GI discomfort.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <strong>Dietary sources to complement gummies</strong>
          <p>Almonds (80mg/oz), spinach (78mg/half cup), dark chocolate (64mg/oz), avocado (58mg/avocado), pumpkin seeds (156mg/oz). Most Americans still fall short of the RDA even with a balanced diet.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <strong>Signs of deficiency</strong>
          <p>Muscle cramps and twitching, difficulty falling asleep, anxiety, restless legs, headaches, and fatigue. If you experience these symptoms, magnesium deficiency is a likely contributing factor.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <strong>Drug interactions</strong>
          <p>Magnesium can reduce absorption of certain antibiotics (tetracyclines, fluoroquinolones) and bisphosphonates. Separate dosing by 2-4 hours. Consult your pharmacist if you take these medications.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

