    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Magnesium Gummies for Sleep</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What type of magnesium is best for sleep?</summary>
      <p>Magnesium glycinate is the best form for sleep. It is chelated with glycine — an amino acid that has independent sleep-promoting properties. A 2015 study in <em>Neuropsychopharmacology</em> found that glycine supplementation improved subjective sleep quality, reduced sleep onset latency, and decreased daytime sleepiness. Glycinate is also the most bioavailable form (25-30% absorption) and the gentlest on the digestive system. Magnesium citrate is a close second but can cause GI issues. Magnesium oxide should be avoided for sleep due to its 4% absorption rate.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much magnesium should I take for sleep?</summary>
      <p>For sleep improvement, most clinical studies use 200-400mg of elemental magnesium daily, taken 30-60 minutes before bedtime. The RDA is 310-320mg for women and 400-420mg for men. Start with 200mg and increase to 400mg if needed. Taking more than 400mg from supplements alone may cause GI discomfort, particularly with citrate or oxide forms.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>When should I take magnesium gummies for sleep?</summary>
      <p>Take magnesium gummies 30-60 minutes before your target bedtime. This timing allows for digestion and absorption. Magnesium glycinate can be taken with or without food, while citrate is better taken with food to reduce GI risk. Consistency matters more than precise timing — taking magnesium at the same time every night helps establish a bedtime routine signal.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How long does magnesium take to improve sleep?</summary>
      <p>Magnesium supplementation for sleep typically requires 1-2 weeks of consistent daily use before measurable improvements appear. This is because magnesium works by correcting an underlying mineral deficiency rather than inducing acute sedation. A 2012 clinical trial found significant improvements after 8 weeks, with some participants noticing initial benefits within the first two weeks. Allow a minimum of 4 weeks before evaluating effectiveness.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take magnesium gummies with melatonin?</summary>
      <p>Yes, magnesium and melatonin can be taken together safely and may have complementary effects. Magnesium supports natural melatonin production by activating the enzyme N-acetyltransferase. A 2012 study found that magnesium supplementation increased serum melatonin levels in elderly adults with insomnia. However, many sleep specialists recommend trying magnesium alone first, as it may eliminate the need for exogenous melatonin.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Does magnesium cause vivid dreams or nightmares?</summary>
      <p>Magnesium supplementation may increase dream vividness in some users, but this is not the same as the vivid nightmares commonly reported with melatonin. Magnesium supports deeper REM sleep, the phase during which most dreaming occurs. This is generally considered a positive sign that sleep architecture is improving. If vivid dreaming is bothersome, reducing the dose slightly may help.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is magnesium glycinate or citrate better for sleep?</summary>
      <p>Magnesium glycinate is superior to citrate for sleep. It has 10-20% higher bioavailability, causes virtually no GI side effects, and the glycine chelation itself has clinically documented sleep benefits. The only advantage of citrate is cost — it is 3-5 times cheaper to manufacture. For users who tolerate citrate well and prioritize value, it remains an effective option.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can magnesium gummies replace prescription sleep medication?</summary>
      <p>Magnesium gummies are not a replacement for prescription sleep medication and should not be used as such without physician guidance. However, for individuals with mild sleep difficulties related to magnesium deficiency, supplementation may be sufficient to resolve the issue without medication. If you currently take prescription sleep medication and want to transition to magnesium, work with your physician to develop a gradual tapering plan.</p>
    </details>

